         <abstract>
            <p>The Martin Report has defended fixed commissions and argued for consolidating all securities trading activities into a single national exchange. The SEC's recent Institutional Investor Study, on the other hand, attacked fixed commissions as a source of many of the current problems in the securities markets, and argued for a market "in which all qualified broker-dealers... may participate," with efficiency encouraged by the forces of competition. According to the author, who directed the SEC Study, adoption of the Martin proposals would forcibly eliminate competition among qualified market makers, thereby preserving the monopolistic features of the present market and perpetuating the problems.</p>
          </abstract>
